(now in the Bodleian Library) of Caedmon's metrical Paraphrase‚ was one of Milton's friends, and may have shown the MS.‚ or may have communicated the contents to him. Some have supposed that Milton took some hints from this poem for the framework of Paradise Losa—At p. 109 is a remark showing Milton’s displeasure at the marriage of Charles I. with one of the Roman Catholic beliefi—At p. 179 he brands the Law F rench, then (and for nearly a century later) used in Law Report-s, as “gibberisl1.’'—At p. 180 his remark on the tendenoy of the English to follow F rench fashions would seem to lead to the inference that the sentence was written soon after the marriage of Charles I.
